The paper deals with computer vision problems such as human activity recognition, background reconstruction, and multi-object tracking, which are typically associated with the computer vision sub-category cs.CV. The paper proposes a novel algorithm for global motion compensation, which involves matching local keypoints of each frame and formulating a keypoint-based congealing problem. This suggests that the paper could also be relevant to the robotics sub-category cs.RO, as well as the multimedia sub-category cs.MM, which deals with video processing. The paper also involves iterative updates to the transformation of each frame, which suggests that it could be relevant to the machine learning sub-category cs.LG. Finally, the paper proposes a new algorithm for global motion compensation, which suggests that it could be relevant to the artificial intelligence sub-category cs.AI.
